Serpentes-USAR 10 (Urban Search & Rescue)

Type: robotic | Generated: 12/6/2025

Executive Summary

A modular, hyper-redundant snake robot designed for penetrating deep into collapsed rubble. It features a high-torque orthogonal joint system, a ruggedized multispectral sensing head, and a hybrid tether/battery power system to ensure operation within 10cm gaps.

Validation Checks

  • Missing Component: The assembly steps reference a 'central processing unit in the first body segment', but no dedicated Compute Module or CPU is listed in the 'partsList'. A robot with SLAM and thermal fusion capabilities requires a dedicated processing unit.
  • Physical Constraint/Geometry: The rigid segment length of 10cm combined with a 9.5cm outer diameter makes traversing a 90-degree bend in a 10cm pipe physically impossible (geometric jamming) unless the bend radius is very large. The segments need to be shorter or the pipe diameter constraint larger relative to the robot.
  • Safety/Validation Specification: The tether tension validation is set to 20kg. For a 10kg robot operating in rubble where jamming is likely, a 2x safety factor for extraction is insufficient. 50kg+ is a standard safety margin for retrieval.
  • Power Logic: The 'Distributed Battery Units' are listed as being in 'every second segment' (8 total), but the interaction with the 'Smart Tether' power and the 24V bus needs explicit management (e.g., a power distribution board or management within the Compute Module) which was not detailed.
